review_blob: Excellent dunkel-esque dark lager with requisite slightly roasted caramel malt, expressed with notes of chalky dry dark chocolate. However, the addition of earthy hops with cool bitterness akin to a Pilsner makes for a distinctive brew. Smooth medium-bodied palate on draft, with a crisp white head atop a rich mahogany-hued body. Overall another delicious fine-tuned beer from Brooklyn!

Kicking off a bachelor party weekend with something a little exotic! This toasted coconut-infused brown ale was a deliciously non-conventional brew, struck a perfect balance of flavorful but not overwhelming coconut flavor with a more traditional toasted caramel malt base. Aroma is toasted malt with just a slight hint of the coconut notes, along with some English-style chocolate malt and earthiness. Taste is smooth coconut-accented maltiness- the coconut takes the place of the nutty note that is more standard for the style. Finishes slightly earthy but refreshing, an excellent beer to change things up occasionally.

Some of the more delicious sak I have tried recently; enjoyed a bottle of this paired with a couple different meals from standard fried rice with seaweed to tuna steaks, very versatile in pairing. Slightly grainy yellow color, aroma of mango and sweet alcohol. Medium-bodied with an excellent full flavor of fruit and rice-grain, peppery agave finish. Very prominent alcohol tinge throughout, but not in an offensive way. Overall quite enjoyable.

Going on memory for this review, but I recall a rich amber appearance with a steady and balanced head, with an aroma of caramel malt. Flavorful malty notes, with bread, caramel, fruit all present, with a mild hoppiness if you look for it. Highlight was the appearance, otherwise a standard drinkable but authentic rendition of the irish red style.
beer_name: Flying Dog Lucky SOB Irish Red

review_blob: A nice amber lager from Shiner, pours an excellent clean amber color with lots of white lacing and foam, very classic look. Aroma is a subdued caramel maltiness, reminds me of a weaker version of a Brooklyn lager or original Shiner Bock. Taste likewise is a couple layers of caramel malt and grain notes, pleasant and not too sophisticated. Finishes clean, light-to-medium bodied. Decent flavor but a bit thin.

Hmm very good but did not strike me as tropical as advertised. Pours a very fresh appealing golden copper color with lots of fluffy head, aroma of light resin and pacific hops, not as resiny as a full-on West coast IPA but not fruity and sweet either. The strongest aspect of taste was the flavorful warm caramel maltiness, lots of citrus hops, some slight sweet mango, but more generic pacific hoppiness than specifically tropical notes. Bitter citrus hop finish, smooth medium bodied texture. Solid IPA, but not very distinctive.
beer_name: Sierra Nevada Beer Camp Tropical IPA

review_blob: A thoroughly luxurious Belgian abbey ale, Chimay Blue pours a flawless ruby-brown color with a small but steady white head. Aroma of rich slightly roasty brown sugar- caramel maltiness, along with yeasty candy apple notes. Some cocoa-coffee notes also, this is the first abbey ale I've sampled with a coffee malt accent to it. Taste is caramel malt, candy yeast, some dark chocolate, vanilla, and red fruit. Slight boozy tinge but minor. Mouthfeel however strikes me as an unusually thin and weaker texture, the low point for this brew in my opinion. Overall still a rich and flavorful rendition of the style, less delicate in its flavor profile than others. Not my personal favorite but well done.

A true crossover brew, this offering from Allagash features both stout and Belgian aspects, with a strong roasted coffee appearance and flavor, along with a sweet Belgian yeast contrast. Some chocolate cocoa flavors as well. Mouthfeel is only an average smoothness with a slightly bitter roasty finish. I found the flavor profile exceptional but everything else is just par for the course.!Decent and different, seems like it has weaker points but a distinguished beer overall.

A decent American stout, emphasis on the roasted coffee bean flavors. Actually doubles down on a nuanced rich coffee roasted malt flavor, and doesn't have much else to add complexity other than some bitter pacific hoppiness in the finish. Slick and medium bodied texture. Jet black appearance. Ballast Point is a solid West Coast brewery.

An absolutely delicious and finely crafted beer! Fresh aroma of floral hops and a clean full golden appearance, with hints of Belgian yeast wafting up from the pillowy head. Rich flavor of sweet malt with light peppercorn spicy flavor, mild bitterness from the soft tropical hops. Mild carbonation and medium body makes for a very smooth palate. Exceedingly fresh and crisp all around, no alcohol tinge whatsoever. Finished clean and refreshing with a slight peppery pineapple hoppy flavor. Paired deliciously well with some olive encrusted salmon. Highly recommended!

The bottle I'm looking at says "Huger street IPA", but everything else points to this beer being a heavily pacific-hopped wheat beer and seems to be the same brew identified above. This is an interesting one for sure from Palmetto, something of an IPA-wheat beer crossover. Fresh and distinct notes of both wheat and citrus hops in the aroma, which anticipates the taste of both sweet wheat and bitter citrus and tropical hops. Some caramel malt in the background also, truly as if one had mixed a wheat and IPA together. The main downside for me however was the apparent addition of rye to the mix, which was a very sharp and unpleasant note that did not complement the rest of the flavor profile. I think they tried to include a bit too much with this one, but it's alright overall.

This Trappist brew is a subtle middle-intensity malty ale, with caramel and fruity brown sugar malty notes, along with some yeasty sweetness. The appearance for me was a weak point, my bottle poured a hazy ember red hue with a minimal fizzy head, nice color but nothing exceptional. On the other hand, I loved the nutty and barley-caramel malt aroma, reminiscent of a baked apple pie. Taste is pleasantly fruity and sweet, Belgian yeast notes are present but understated. Enjoyable overall, but not my preferred abbey ale.

Definitely a Sottish ale, featuring standard peaty/earthy notes and chocolate/caramel malt notes as befitting the style. Appearance is an average earthy amber-brown color with average white lacing. Aroma of soil, peat, caramel malt. Earth and caramel malt in the flavor, a nice if average rendition of the style. Subtle hint of red fruit in the finish. Interesting and well-crafted.
beer_name: DuClaw Foundation Series #2: 80 Shilling Scottish Ale

review_blob: Interesting golden ale variation, bubbly golden appearance with aromas of flowery hops and sweet malt, no oak on the nose as far as I could tell. A bit more subtle woody oak in the flavor, light and vanilla-like. Sweet golden malt taste predominates, some herbal grassy bitterness with the oak in the finish. Light-bodied. Good but a bit strange, I prolly would not sample this particular I&G beer again but will consider some of their other offerings.
beer_name: Innis & Gunn Rare Oak Pale Ale

review_blob: I've been looking forward to sampling shiner's first effort at an IPA, and this is a good but incomplete rendition of the style. Fresh copper gold appearance, nice proportionate head. Aroma of caramel malt, bitter pacific hops, hint of resin. Flavor is citrus and pine hops, caramel malt, very tasty but lacking in flavor intensity. Lighter medium body, very soft on the palate, no sticky resin bitterness for an IPA. Overall this was an enjoyable beer with a good flavor profile, just needs to be amplified to be something exceptional.

Enjoyed this phenomenal beer with a hearty well-done steak last night, this rich and strong full-flavored imperial stout is among some of the best brews I have ever sampled. Thick black oil appearance with a coffee bean brown head, lots of roasted coffee and charred cocoa/wood flavors in the aroma. Flavor is an absolutely delicious mix of roast coffee, oak, cocoa (not chocolate in my opinion, just a bitter dark cocoa), and some notes of red fruit, almost cherry-like without the tartness or sweetness. Interestingly I did not observe any booziness or alcohol tinge in this beer, apart from the label on the bottle, nothing betrays the high ABV of this brew. Definitely warming though, and with a satisfying bitter earthy malt finish. Well done!

An interesting and distinctive interpretation of the Helles style, lots of soft tropical fruit on the nose and in the taste, along with lots of sweet grainy malt. Some light grassy noble hops, but with a fruity pear-like accent. Soft water palate with lots of carbonation, decently refreshing. Low point was the appearance, very weak clear yellow, excessive bubbly carbonation. Not amazing, but different, and I would drink this again.

Not Thomas Creek's most exemplary brew, a rather basic pilsner with a light bready malt flavor, hint of noble hops with a grassy-lemon finish. Appearance was sub-par, just a bland yellow color with some light white head, aroma of the same flavors described above. Light-bodied, just a very average unadventurous pilsner, I would not bother sampling this again.

Hmm not the best session IPA I've had, but not bad either. Lemon-colored amber appearance with a lemony citrus hop aroma, soapy head. Funky thin palate, taste is an alright resiny pacific hops and some light bready malt. More lemon tartness to the citrus hops in the finish. Really a bit disappointing overall, not something I would care to session.

Not your usual winter warmer, this Shiner seasonal goes for a unique fruity and sweet dessert angle instead of the more traditional spice-centric and rich alcoholic winter style. Features sweet peachy notes and nutty pecan flavors as described, which are actually light and fresh on the palate and pleasantly balanced with some bready malt. Appearance is thoroughly clear for being a self-described wheat beer, also I'm uneasy about the caramel color added, not sure what they were going for on that aspect. But still a pleasant and enjoyable beer overall, this may be one of the few fruit-infused beers that wasn't syrupy sweet or overbearingly fruity. Well-balanced.

An interesting and well done stout, pours a dark espresso brown with white lacing to contrast, aroma of light roasty malt with bitter cocoa accents. Flavor of smoky roasted malt, some subtle chocolate malt sweetness. Medium-to-light mouthfeel, thin but not watery. Coffee roast and cocoa in the finish. An interesting variety of layered roasty malt flavors present overall, that doesn't overwhelm the palate and indeed finishes on a relatively crisp note. Enjoyable.

Well this is one of the better chocolate-infused winter beers I've sampled, features a more natural chocolate bean flavor that does not overwhelm the underlying chocolate and caramel malt flavors. Subtle red fruit flavors as befitting a bock, also a slight vanilla note contrasting with the chocolatiness. Mouthfeel is medium-bodied, some creaminess. Well done and better than most other chocolate beers that tend towards a more artificial or overpowering chocolate flavor.

First beer of the new year! I am impressed by this delicious dunkelweizen-style winter warmer, which features both licorice-sweet wheat flavors as well as caramel and roasted chocolate malty flavors. Pours a murky brown-black, lots of white foam, with a sweet candy yeast aroma. Slight alcohol tartness in the finish, standard for a warmer. Interesting and enjoyable, paired well with the Parmesan cheese from my entree. Another well-done Anchor beer!

Toasting the New Year 2016 with this brew, and satisfied with this choice! This unique French Belgian-style beer features standard yeasty and fruity notes on the nose and on the palate, but also has a grainy/ malty base underlining those flavors. The spicy notes, particularly a candied ginger accent, also show through. Minty notes in the finish. Appearance is a slightly hazy yellow-gold, standard for the style, but also has an exceptionally long-lasting head. Interesting crossover/ halfway point between a Belgian style and a spiced earthy brown ale. Distinctive and recommended!

I suppose this is vintage Sierra Nevada, the original stout from the storied old days, and it does not disappoint! Pours a rich oak-hued black appearance with a solid white foamy head. Aroma is a blast of strong roasted coffee bean and chocolate malt. Subtle cocoa and earthy pine wood notes in the aroma as well. Taste is an exceedingly flavorful mix of roasty coffee and caramel malts and an earthy hop bitterness. This west coast stout is definitely distinct from its European cousins. Finishes with a cocoa bar bitterness. Was not as full-bodied or creamy as claimed by others, but still a superior brew!

Essentially a low-budget IPA, this so-called "IPL" does feature some descent citrus, herbal and resiny hoppy notes, but has a cheaper cereal-malt base that betrays this beer's industrial lager roots. Also very thin on the palate with a sticky unpleasant mouthfeel. The appearance was a pleasant bronze golden color with white lacing. Hop-centric brewing isn't Yuengling's strong suite, but this is an alright brew. Look for Sierra Nevada's Hoppy Lager for the real deal.

I think this brew is a bit superior to Star lager, the only other Ghanian beer I've had the opportunity to sample. Still essentially the same style - euro macro lager - but in this case, features less adjunct presence. Pours a bronzed golden color, just looks faded and not as appealing as others. Aroma is grainy malt, grassy hops, but also some skunkiness. Taste is a grainy and sweet maltiness, a faint hint of adjuncts but only if you look for it, not too bad. Flavor is a bit weak and thin, just a macro lager that avoids drifting too far in the adjunct direction. Hoppiness is light and pleasant, drinkable but nothing exceptional. On par with the standard euro lagers.

Was able to sample this African brew (my first beer from Africa I believe) courtesy of a good friend from Ghana. I understand Star lager is an authentic local favorite in its country of origin, and it's not bad for being a standard euro-macro-lager. Pours an exceptionally fresh and full-bodied bronze/gold appearance, more impressive than your average pale lager. Lots of lacing and foam releases a strong grainy and hoppy aroma. The hoppiness is distinctive but in a slightly cooked herbal way, interesting but a bit funky. The sweet grainy malt also has a corn-tinged undertone to it, but is not too unpleasant. In the aftertaste, the noble hops turn sour and my impression is that the hops used are not of the highest quality as one can imagine, but at least they stand out, which is more than Heineken can say. Finished a bit watery and the adjuncts are noticeable, but again it's not bad for what it is.

I found this to be quite the enjoyable Pilsner, which seems to be underappreciated based on prior reviews. Enjoyed a fresh bottle of this at home, this beer pours a nice golden straw color with nice white frothy foam and lacing. Aroma is a rich grainy malt flavor with a slight straw/grassy hoppiness. The taste is likewise a full-flavored pale malt and grain with some slight noble hops in the finish. Medium bodied but very quaffable. Pleasant sweet malty aftertaste. Exceedingly fresh, a distinctly malt-centric Pilsner, with just enough hops to stay true to the style. Well done.

Enjoying this summer seasonal a bit out of season in November, but it's still a pleasant light IPA. The aroma is particularly pleasant, rich citrus cascade hops and sweet maltiness. The appearance is a basic slightly hazy golden hue with white head, more akin to a lager. The flavor is light yet robust, features crisp resiny citrus hoppiness contrasted with a light sweet grainy malt, a hint of grassy hops also in the finish. Light bodied and clean finishing, not a personal favorite but recommended overall.

Recently sampled from a can, I was pleasantly surprised with this offering from Terrapin. Pours a honey accented-orange standard pale ale color, with a white foamy head. Aroma of brown sugar and sweet malt, with pacific hops. The rye comes through subtly in the taste with a sweet rye malt flavor with toasty brown sugary malt also; there is a solid hoppy bitterness to be sure, but this is well balanced by the strong malty notes. Features a solid medium bodied mouthfeel also. This is an exceptionally good beer overall, more enjoyable than the Hopsecutioner. A recommended malt-centric distinctive pale ale.

I'm writing this from memory, but I've sampled this brew twice in the last week on draft fresh in its hometown (on tap at Bourbon of Columbia, SC - a great local spot!). This beer is an exceedingly delicious and balanced chocolate and rye accented brown ale, fresh tasting and fitting for a cool October afternoon. Chocolate malt is predominant in the aroma, some cocoa bitterness also. Pours a translucent brown color with lots of lacing and white foamy head. Light chocolate and sweet malty flavors in the taste, light rye spiciness, very delicate but complex with some hop bitterness in the background. The palate is clean and light-bodied, not something strong that will overwhelm you tastebuds but thoroughly enjoyable. Just a great light brown ale!

From a fresh bottle, this interesting collaborative rendition pours a surprisingly faint clear amber appearance, lighter than usual for a marzen, almost seems like a halfway point between marzen and Helles. The aroma is distinctly German noble hops and grainy caramel malt. Taste likewise has grassy hops followed by a light malty taste with a sour earthy finish. Light bodied, smooth, and just a lighter beer overall, almost more fitting for the summer than the Fall. Good but not my personal favorite Oktoberfest bier.

Ah just another exceptional brew from Sierra Nevada. Not quite is heavy and overbearing as a double IPA but definitely a bit more potent than a standard IPA, this "extra IPA" finds a drinkable balance in between. Both on tap and from a can, pours a brilliant burnished bronze appearance with plenty of white foam. The aroma is a blunt piney hoppiness, but in the flavor this beer provides a variety of both pacific piney and fruity hop notes and also a sweet caramel malt contrast. Full-flavored and not-quite-full-bodied. Aftertaste is both bitter and sweet- but not bittersweet- haha. Thoroughly enjoyable and although I think I'll stick to the classics flagship pale ale, I'm glad I tried this.

Doubling down on Aecht Schlenkerla this evening, as a doppelbock aficionado I enjoyed this smoked variation of the style. The aroma is not as overtly smoky as the marzen rauchbier rendition, more of a subtle burnt oaky aroma with the standard chocolate malt present. The appearance is unusually lighter and more transparent for the D-Bock style, and the white head receded more quickly, so it seemed. In addition to the forward smoky taste, there is a warm and delicious chocolate and rich caramel maltiness, definitely recognizable as a D-bock with an almost maple syrup-like taste. Interesting and enjoyable, and I do believe the smoke complements the chocolate well to create a s'mores-like taste, although I would prefer an unsmoked D-Bock to this. Also should be noted there was no booziness despite the 8% Abv.

Uniquely exotic and more sophisticated than its critics give it credit for, this most renowned rauchbier in the world provides a distinctive and enjoyable Marzen experience featuring the classic Bamberg smokiness that defines this style. From an imported bottle, this beer pours a rich caramel brown color with a generous khaki-white foamy head, looks more like a solid marzen than most marzens I have seen, impressive appearance. The aroma gives off a strong and blunt "smoked ham" flavor that may be understandably off-putting to some, but this overt and overwhelming smokiness does not carry over into the flavor, which to be sure has a strong smoky element but without the meaty ham notes. Indeed, the flavor reveals an excellent interplay of smoky and classic caramel malty notes, along with some subtle cocoa in the finish. Truly, other than in the aroma, the smokiness is not overpowering and allows the classic marzen flavors to show through. A delightful culinary experience overall.

A bit more hefty than other craft lagers, this brew is a relatively more full flavored and full bodied example of the style. Pours a golden yellow appearance with proportionate head and lacing. Aroma is noble hops and sweet maltiness. Flavor is likewise light hoppiness and biscuit malt, a bit too much malty sweetness for my taste. A bit too thick on the palate also. Interesting but not my favorite lager rendition.
beer_name: Anchor Zymaster Series No. 1 California Lager

review_blob: A very pleasant classic west coast IPA. From the bottle, pours a standard copper orange appearance with a touch of haziness. Aroma is exceptionally rich with resiny notes of orange and grapefruit hops and some toasty maltiness. Tropical and piney hops in the taste with some moderate maltiness, all at a moderate flavor intensity. Medium bodied, and relatively less bitter in the finish for the style. Very drinkable and refreshing, not as hardcore when it comes to the hoppiness. Well done overall.

I think this is possibly the best beer I've ever had from a can. Pours an exceptionally refined opaque ruby brown color with a long lasting foamy khaki head. Aroma is rich chocolate malt and some coffee-like notes, some slight smokiness. On the palate, perfectly medium-bodied and creamy, full of dark chocolate malty flavors and a smoky cocoa flavor reminiscent of burnt s'mores. Just a slight boozy betrayal of the high ABV in the finish to detract from the palate, but all in all this is a delicious beer that is well done in every category!

Well sampled this with some delicious authentic Indian cuisine, I suppose this beer has as much a right as any to claim to be the authentic beer of India, so pairs well in that sense. Then again, really nothing distinctive about this macro lager, although was not inoffensive and seemed very fresh and clean tasting, no pungent cardboard malts or stale hops here. Just standard sweet pale malt, more floral than grassy hop accents, light bodied but not watery. Very yellow golden color and fizzy. Nothing "Indian" about it as you can imagine, but I'd take it over Heineken any day.

Hmm not a bad IPA, just a bit on the lighter side. Pours a relatively more pale copper orange color, some weak but presentable lacing and foam. Aroma is quite appetizing, rich maltiness and grapefruit and resin hops. Taste is the same, lots of bready malt and grapefruit hops, moderately bitter. Balanced but not subtle. Palate is thin and doesn't stick in the finish, which could be a plus for casual sessioning. A little bit of sweet fruit in the aftertaste too, fresh and summery. Not too sophisticated but pleasant overall.

Well most recently sampled a pint of this from a freshly tapped keg in Columbia; pours more of an orange accented amber hue, great head retention throughout the whole pint, although the hazy appearance was a bit unappealing. Aroma of brown sugar and caramel, perhaps some citrus notes. In the taste, an earthy caramel flavor predominates, appropriate bitter finish, just average. Palate was reasonably smooth, sticky in the finish. Just a decent ESB, not too adventurous for the style.

Well I just ordered this expecting a standard double IPA, but I was pleasantly surprised at this rather exotic and iconoclastic brew! This brew is half dopplebock and half IPA, truly fascinating! Pours a lighter amber off-brown color, slightly reminiscent of a standard IPA copper color but much darker. Aroma of rich burnt caramel and some piney resin, as well as a hint of vanilla. The caramel turns to chocolate malt in the taste, with a citrus orange hoppiness In the background, some other caramel maltiness. Essentially tastes like a chocolate dipped mandarin orange, with a bit of a boozy bite in the finish. Aftertaste of chocolate and grapefruit hops. I could see how others may find this off-putting, but I found it quite enjoyable! Extreme indeed, but memorably and deliciously so!
beer_name: Thomas Creek Up the Creek Extreme IPA

review_blob: From a well kept imported bottle, this Hefeweizen pours a bright hazy golden color, with an impressive head that lasted the entire pint. Aroma is soft and floral, truly reminiscent of the mountain breeze of southern Germany, if I may, haha. Very enjoyable notes of sweet wheat, light banana, and a hint of grassy floral (hoppy?) notes in the flavor. Light bodied, pleasantly less filling than other hefeweizens. More of a delicate flavor overall, but quite the effort to detect the subtleties to this classic brew.

I continue to have positive experiences with Blue Point's line up of brews, this their IPA was a pleasant exceptionally malty rendition of the style. Standard amber/copper IPA appearance, aroma is citrus and herbal hops and warm malty notes. Taste has a strong caramel malt baseline with a suddenly tart piney bitter finish. Balanced overall but there is more flavor intensity on the malty side than on the hoppy side. Finishes dry, medium bodied. Surprisingly strong ABV, no boozy notes in the taste. I would drink this again.

Well this was a truly exceptional and unique brew, which successfully combined elements of both an IPA and a Belgian saison. On draft from a freshly tapped keg, this poured a hazy wheaty golden color, with an aroma of west coast hops and yeast. Taste is very complex and also well balanced, with an initial sweetness of Belgian yeast, followed by fruity hops, mostly grapefruit, and also with a subtle bready maltiness throughout. Relatively light on the palate, fresh and not musty as some other farmhouse style ales. Finishes clean, and the hefty ABV surprises you. Definitely a distinctive beer worth trying!
beer_name: Boulevard Smokestack Series - Tank 7 Farmhouse Ale

review_blob: Wow, this is simply an excellent beer! This variation on the west coast pale ale style pours an amber-accented orange color, with a rich foamy head. Aroma of citrus fruit, predominantly grapefruit and resin, with a sweet malty undertone. The taste is exceedingly balanced, features solid piney hoppy notes with fruity pacific hop flavors, along with a sweet warm toffee caramel malt. The hoppy bitterness is present but subdued, fine tuned. Lighter bodied but has a refreshing full flavored mouthfeel. Finishes on a bitter grapefruit note. All around just a delicious ale, I will be buying this again!
beer_name: HeBrew Genesis Dry Hopped Session Ale

review_blob: From the bottle, this German import pours an unusually murky and hazy apricot appearance, looks rather funky, although the foamy head looks appetizing. Aroma is a bit more classic and pleasant, with light grassy noble hops, some bready malt, fresh and light. On the palate, this pils is strikingly thin, very watery in an unpleasant way. On the other hand, the flavor is a more well done pils profile, with bitter noble hops and a sweetbread pale malt balance. An ok beer overall, but not highly recommended. Reminded me of Stella Artois, but I would prefer the latter.

Enjoyed a few pints of this at a dinner party one stormy night in Columbia SC. From a growler fresh from the brewery 20 minutes down the road, this Porter poured a chocolately brown color, with an eggshell off-white head, moderate lacing, standard for the style. The aroma though hits you before the appearance, with a strong chocolately and vanilla aroma, almost like a sweet dessert. Forward taste of milk chocolate and vanilla bean in the flavor, but this is however certainly not a dessert beer, as there is a roasty and nutty malt base underneath that provides a balancing contrast. Medium bodied and smooth with lesser carbonation, very drinkable, with a cocoa finish. Quite distinctive, excellent complexity, well done!

Another delightful ESB out of Asheville and another success from Green Man. On tap down in Cola SC, this ESB pours a dark amber color, reminiscent of maple syrup (the color not the viscosity!) moderate white head, stays frothy. Aroma of caramel malt herbal hops, toffee. Taste is very nutty, malty and also some bitter hops. Medium-bodied, earthy finish, all around just a pleasant and tasty ale. Not quite as good as Oysterhouse's ESB but a close second. I would definitely drink this again.
